I"¯<p><img src="/assets/img/cpp/shellpp.jpg" alt="Shell++ - An Object Oriented Shell Script" /></p>

<p><a href="https://github.com/alexst07/shell-plus-plus">Shell++</a> is a programming language that aims to bring functionalities from modern languages, such as ease of manipulation of data structures, object-oriented programming, functional programming and others including Shell Script.</p>

<h1 id="installation">Installation</h1>
<p>Clone the repository recursively:</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash">git clone <span class="nt">--recurse-submodules</span> <span class="nt">-j8</span> https://github.com/alexst07/shell-plus-plus</code></pre></figure>

<!-- QUADRADO -->
<script async="" src="//pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/js/adsbygoogle.js"></script>

<p><ins class="adsbygoogle" style="display:inline-block;width:336px;height:280px" data-ad-client="ca-pub-2838251107855362" data-ad-slot="5351066970"></ins>
<script>
(adsbygoogle = window.adsbygoogle || []).push({});
</script></p>

<p>After cloned, we realized that it uses <a href="https://en.terminalroot.com.br/how-to-compile-your-programs-with-cmake/">CMake</a>, if you export the <code class="highlighter-rouge">CXX</code> variable, you may be able to use another compiler, but you will need: CMake, <a href="https://en.terminalroot.com.br/gcc-vs-llvm-which-is-the-best-compiler/">GCC</a> and <a href="https://en.terminalroot.com.br/how-to-create-a-makefile/">GNU Make</a>.</p>

<p>Some distros offer the package with essential tools for building binaries, if you use <a href="https://en.terminalroot.com.br/meet-devuan-gnu-linux-a-debian-without-systemd/">Debian</a>, <a href="https://en.terminalroot.com.br/customize-your-ubuntu-with-wayland-sway-ulauncher-waybar/">Ubuntu</a>, <a href="https://en.terminalroot.com.br/how-to-customize-your-linux-mint-with-i3-polybar-rofi/">Mint</a> and simlares, just install the package: build-essentials. If you use <a href="https://en.terminalroot.com.br/how-to-create-an-ebuild-on-gentoo/">Gentoo</a>, you donâ€™t need to install anything.</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash"><span class="c"># you can change the compiler with this command:</span>
<span class="nb">export </span><span class="nv">CXX</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="si">$(</span>which clang++<span class="si">)</span>

<span class="nb">mkdir </span>build <span class="o">&amp;&amp;</span> <span class="nb">cd </span>build
cmake ..
make</code></pre></figure>

<p>After building the binary, it can be found at: <code class="highlighter-rouge">./shell/shpp</code>. You can run one:</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash"><span class="nb">sudo </span>make <span class="nb">install</span></code></pre></figure>

<blockquote>
  <p>Remembering that you can also execute the binary directly.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>Basic usage example:</p>
<h2 id="hello-world">Hello, World!</h2>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash"><span class="nb">cat</span> <span class="o">&lt;&lt;</span> <span class="no">EOF</span><span class="sh"> &gt; hello.sh
print("Hello, Shell++")
</span><span class="no">EOF
</span>shpp hello.sh</code></pre></figure>

